Suppose we on the other hand a person as miserable as this world can make him, poor so as to beg;
〈 in non-Latin alphabet 〉 . full of Sores and Ulcers, so as not able to help himself; destitute of Friends, so as to be cast at the Rich man's gate;
〈 in non-Latin alphabet 〉 . hunger-starved so as to need the very crumbs which fell from the other's table; contemned so as not to be regarded though lying at the gate, in the passage and view of all; or if taken notice of, yet so as not to be relieved; naked, so as not to have wherewith to cover his Body, or to defend his sores from the cold, and that found more pity among the dogs than men, while alive (for they came and licked his sores); and when dead through want, pain and anguish, found as little charity to bury him. Thus far we find them as unlike as can be in their present condition.

